<span> The son of a Russian oil manager who acquired Maltese citizenship was imprisoned in the United Kingdom after admitting to have recycled more than 14 million euros in "counters", along with a member.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>
<span>Semen Kuksov, the twenty-four-year-old son of the Russian businessman Vladimir Anatolyevich Kuksov, was imprisoned in February for five years and seven months after admitted his role in money laundering.&nbsp;</span>
&nbsp;
Both the father and the son appear on the last list of people who were granted Maltese citizenship in 2022. The elderly Kuksov was not connected to the child's criminal case. It seems that the Kuksov was granted Maltese citizenship weeks before Malta suspended the sale of passports to wealthy Russians in the wake of Russia's invasion of Ukraine in February 2022.&nbsp; More than a year later, Semen Kuksov was accused by the United Kingdom Crown Prosecution Service of recycled £12 million (about €14 million) in "counters", along with a member.&nbsp;
<br> Kuksov is accused of having played "a leading role in the management of the illegal enterprise that recycled large sums of cash from criminal origin after compensation". &nbsp;&nbsp;According to a press release of the Crown Prosecution Service, Kuksov and his partner managed couriers to collect criminal money and deliver recycled money abroad.&nbsp;Hanno contributed to recycle a total of £12.32 million in the UK and €168.950 in Ireland.

