AGI - The war in Ukraine and the increase in geopolitical tensions last year caused the increased increase in global military spending since 2009:> is the fact that emerges from the analysis of the International Institute of Peace Research (the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute, the Sipri). Investments in weapons have reached the record figure of 2.290 billion euros, 6.8% more in real terms than 2022 and 2.3% of the global GDP. A expenditure monopolized by the US and NATO.<br> The undisputed domain is of the United States with an investment of 860 billion euros, 2.3% more, and 37% of global expenditure (three times higher than that of China, second of the ranking), 68% of expenditure of the 31 member countries of NATO.<br> The study also highlights the increase in investment in the defence of European NATO countries, which now account for 28% of those of the entire Alliance, the highest level in a decade, with eleven of them above the commitment of 2% of GDP. Poland, with an annual increase of 75%, shows the highest annual increase in Europe. It should be noted that the total expenditure of members of NATO amounted to 1,260 billion euros, > 55% of the world total.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"The last two years of war in Ukraine have radically changed the prospects of European security states. This change in the perception of the threat is reflected in the target of increasing GDP quotas to military spending," writes Sipri. Russia>, third in the world ranking, has allocated an estimated figure of 102 billion euros, 4.5% globally and 24% more on an annual basis, i.e. 5.9% of its GDP. Ukraine, the eighth world investor in the arms industry, increased its expenditure by 51% to over 60 billion euros, a third of its GDP. With nearly 32 billion euros of military aid received, Ukraine significantly reduced the gap with Russia and total Ukrainian military spending amounted to 91% of Moscow.
&nbsp;
Increased investments have also been made in Asia and the Middle East. China has spent almost 278 billion euros, 6% more and 12% of the total, that is half of the investments in the Asia-Oceania region, according to the Sipri. Therefore, Japan (tenth in the standings) increased its military spending by 11% and also Taiwan by 11%.<br> The Middle East recorded the increase in a decade, equal to 9%, with Saudi Arabia (fifth) as a regional leader, followed by Israel (15), which increased its spending by 24% due to its offensive in the Gaza Strip after the Hamas attacks last October.
&nbsp;
"The great increase in military spending in the Middle East in 2023 reflects the rapidly changing situation in the region, the improvement of diplomatic relations between Israel and several Arab countries in recent years at the outbreak of a great war in Gaza and the fear of a regional conflict," reads again in the document. In Central America and the Caribbean, spending (+54% in 2023) was the fight against organised crime. The sad primacy is Brazil, eighteenth country worldwide, with an expense of 21,5 billion euros, 3.1% more.&nbsp;
